window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2018>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2018","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : PERIOD, FREQUENCY AND AMPLITUDE OF A BODY EXECUTING S.H.M","question":"You are provided with a pendulum bob, a metre rule, a stopwatch, a retort stand with clamp, and other necessary apparatus.    (i) Suspend the pendulum bob from the clamp as illustrated in the diagram.  (ii) Adjust the pendulum such that  AC  = L  = 90 cm  (iii) Displace the pendulum bob slightly such that it oscillates in a vertical plane.  (iv) Measure and record the time  t  for 20 complete oscillations.  (v) Evaluate  T and  &radic;L&nbsp;   (vi) Repeat the procedure for four others values of  L  = 80 cm, 70 cm, 60 cm, and 50 cm.   (vii) Tabulate your readings  (viii) Plot a graph with  T on the vertical axis and  &radic;L&nbsp;  on the horizontal axis.  (ix) Determine the slope,  s , of the graph.  (x) Evaluate g = 4\u03c02s2\\frac{4\u03c0^{2}}{s^{2}}s24\u03c02\u200b  (xi) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/N L(cm) t(s) T = t20\\frac{t}{20}20t\u200b(s)  &radic;L&nbsp; (cm1/2) 1 90 37.4 1.870 9.4872 80 35.4 1.770 8.9443 70 33.5 1.675 8.3674 60 30.9 1.545 7.7465 50 28.31.415 7.071        (ix) s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 1.8\u22124.59\u22127.25\\frac{1.8-4.5}{9-7.25}9\u22127.251.8\u22124.5\u200b = 0.351.75\\frac{0.35}{1.75}1.750.35\u200b = 0.2 scm-1/2    (x) g = 4\u03c02s2\\frac{4\u03c0^{2}}{s^{2}}s24\u03c02\u200b = 4\u00d73.1420.22\\frac{4\u00d73.14^{2}}{0.2^{2}}0.224\u00d73.142\u200b = 986 cms-2 = 9.86 ms-2    (xi)  Precautions:     1. I ensured there was no zero error on the stop clock and metre rule by calibrating them before use and making necessary adjustments.    2. I avoided draughts and air currents in the experimental area to prevent movement of the apparatus, which could affect the accuracy of the readings.    3. I took measures to avoid conical oscillation of the pendulum, ensuring that it oscillated in a purely vertical plane to maintain consistency in the measurements.    4. I repeated measurements multiple times to minimize random errors and improve the reliability of the data.    5. I verified that all equipment was securely set up and free from any mechanical disturbances before starting the experiment.    6. I ensured the environment was stable, with no sudden vibrations that could interfere with the results.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2018>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2018","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : PERIOD, FREQUENCY AND AMPLITUDE OF A BODY EXECUTING S.H.M","question":"Determine from your graph, the period of the pendulum for  L  = 75 cm.    (Provide your answer to 2 d.p e.g 123.123 m)","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"When L = 75 cm,    &radic;L&nbsp; = &radic;75&nbsp; = 8.66 cm-1/2    From the graph, 8.66 cm-1/2 corresponds to period, T = 1.72 s","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2018>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2018","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : SPEED AND ACCELERATION OF S.H.M","question":"A simple pendulum bob is set into simple harmonic motion. Sketch a diagram of the setup and indicate on it; the positions of:  (a) maximum velocity.  (b) maximum acceleration of the bob.","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2018>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2018","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"You are provided with a metre rule, lens, screen, ray box, and other necessary apparatus.  (i) Set up the experiment as shown in the diagram above. Measure and record the diameter  a0 , of the illuminated object.  (ii) Place the object at a distance  x  = 25 cm from the lens. Adjust the screen until a sharp image is obtained on the screen.   (iii) Measure and record the diameter,  a , of the image.  (iv) Measure and record the distance v between the lens and the screen.  (v) Evaluate y = aa0\\frac{a}{a_{0}}a0\u200ba\u200b, P = 1+y2y\\frac{1+y^{2}}{y}y1+y2\u200b and T = x + v.  (vi) Repeat the procedure for  x  = 30 cm, 35 cm, 40 cm and 45 cm. In each case, determine the corresponding values of  a, v, y, P and T.   (vii) Tabulate your results.  (viii) Plot a graph of  P on the vertical axis against  T on the horizontal axis starting both axes from the origin (0,0).  (ix) Determine the slope,  s , of the graph.  (x) Determine the intercept,  c , on the horizontal axis.  (xi) Evaluate k = c2\\frac{c}{2}2c\u200b  (xii) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Table of value    a  = 3.8 cm    S/N x(cm) a(cm) v(cm)  y P(cm) T(cm)1 25.0 5.1 35.2 1.342 2.08760.22 30.0 4.2 34.2 1.105 2.01064.23 35.0 3.227.50.8422.030 62.54 40.0 2.2 26.0 0.579 2.30666.05 45.0 1.6 24.0 0.421 2.796  69.0        (ix) s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 2.75\u22122.06370\u221262.5\\frac{2.75-2.063}{70-62.5}70\u221262.52.75\u22122.063\u200b = 0.6877.5\\frac{0.687}{7.5}7.50.687\u200b = 0.09    (x) c = 39 cm    (xi) k = c2\\frac{c}{2}2c\u200b = 392\\frac{39}{2}239\u200b = 19.5 cm     Precautions:     1. I avoided parallax errors by ensuring my eye was level with the scale while reading the metre rule to maintain accuracy.    2. I ensured the lens was kept upright and stable throughout the experiment to prevent distortions or tilting effects.    3. I repeated all measurements multiple times and recorded the values in a table to ensure consistency and reliability of the results.    4. I cleaned the surface of the lens before use to remove any dust, smudges, or moisture that could affect the clarity and accuracy of the observations.    5. I verified that the metre rule and other measuring instruments were straight and securely positioned to avoid measurement errors.    6. I conducted the experiment in a well-lit environment to ensure clear visibility of the setup and the readings.    7. I ensured proper alignment of the optical elements, such as the lens and object, to achieve precise measurements.    8. I used stable supports for the apparatus to minimize vibrations or movement during the experiment.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2018>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2018","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"Explain the statement, the focal length of a converging lens is 20 cm.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The statement, \"The focal length of a converging lens is 20 cm,\" means that parallel rays of light entering the lens converge at a point, called the principal focus, which is located 20 cm away from the optical center of the lens along its principal axis.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2018>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2018","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT CURVED SURFACES","question":"An object is placed at a distance x from a converging lens of focal length 20 cm. If the magnification of the real image is 5, calculate the value of  x .    (Provide your answer with the unit e.g 123 N)","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"M = 5cm, f = 20cm, x = u    M = vu\\frac{v}{u}uv\u200b    5 = vu\\frac{v}{u}uv\u200b    v = 5u     1f\\frac{1}{f}f1\u200b = 1v\\frac{1}{v}v1\u200b + 1u\\frac{1}{u}u1\u200b    120\\frac{1}{20}201\u200b = 15u\\frac{1}{5}u51\u200bu + 1u\\frac{1}{u}u1\u200b    120\\frac{1}{20}201\u200b = 1+55u\\frac{1+5}{5u}5u1+5\u200b    120\\frac{1}{20}201\u200b = 65u\\frac{6}{5u}5u6\u200b    5u = 20 \u00d7 6    u = 4 \u00d7 6    u = 24 cm    \u2234 x = 24 cm","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2018>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2018","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"You are provided with an ammeter, resistor, key, metre bridge, and other necessary apparatus.    (i) Connect a circuit as shown in the diagram above.  (ii) Close the key and use the jockey to make contact with  AB  at  N  such that  AN = d  = 25 cm   (iii) Read and record the ammeter reading.  (iv) Evaluate I-1.  (v) Repeat the procedures for values of  d  = 35 cm, 50 cm, 65 cm and 80 cm. In each case, record  I and determine I-1.  (vi) Tabulate your results.  (vii) Plot a graph with log I-1 on the vertical axis and d on the horizontal axis.   (viii) Determine the slope,  s of the graph.   (ix) State two precautions taken to obtain accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/N d(cm) I(A) I-1 (A-1 ) log I-11 25 0.65 1.538 0.1872 35  0.55 1.818 0.2603 50 0.44 2.272 0.3564 65 0.30 3.333 0.5235 80 0.23 4.347 0.638         (viii) s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 0.575\u22120.27572.5\u221237.5\\frac{0.575-0.275}{72.5-37.5}72.5\u221237.50.575\u22120.275\u200b = 0.335\\frac{0.3}{35}350.3\u200b = 8.57 \u00d7 10-3 cm-1     Precautions:     1. I ensured the key was opened between readings or when no readings were being taken to prevent the cells from running down.    2. I checked and maintained tight connections throughout the circuit to avoid any power loss or inaccurate readings.    3. I avoided parallax errors by aligning my eye level with the scale while taking readings on the ammeter and metre rule to ensure precision.    4. I repeated all readings multiple times and recorded them to improve accuracy and reliability of the results.    5. I verified the calibration of the ammeter, ensuring there were no zero errors before starting the experiment.    6. I ensured the apparatus was free from vibrations or external disturbances during the experiment to maintain consistent readings.    7. I conducted the experiment in a stable environment, avoiding factors like heat or air currents that could interfere with the results.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2018>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2018","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"Use your graph to determine the value of d when I = 1.5 A.     (Provide your answer to 2 d.p e.g 123.123 N)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"I-1 = 11.5\\frac{1}{1.5}1.51\u200b = 0.667    |log I-1| = 0.176    To get the equation of the line (y = mx + c):    y - 0.575 = 0.00857(x - 72.5)    y - 0.575 = 0.00857x - 0.621    y = 0.00857x - 0.046    So when y = 0.176    0.176 = 0.00857x - 0.046    0.00857x = 0.222    x = 25.90 cm    \u2234 d = 15.17 cm","marks":"21","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2018>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2018","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : RESISTIVITY AND CONDUCTIVITY","question":"State two factors that affect the resistance of a wire.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The resistance of a wire is influenced by several factors, including:    1. Material of the wire: Different materials have varying levels of electrical conductivity. For instance, copper has lower resistance compared to iron due to its higher conductivity.  2. Length of the wire: Resistance is directly proportional to the length of the wire. A longer wire has more collisions between electrons and atoms, increasing resistance.  3. Cross-sectional area: Resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area of the wire. A thicker wire has lower resistance because it allows more electrons to flow.  4. Temperature: As temperature increases, the resistance of most materials (especially metals) increases because atomic vibrations hinder electron flow.  5. Nature of the material: Some alloys, such as nichrome, have higher resistance and are often used in heating elements due to their stability over a wide temperature range.  6. Impurities in the material: The presence of impurities increases resistance by disrupting the uniform structure of the conductor.    These factors collectively determine how easily current flows through a wire.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"}];